ğŸ§ª Example Usage

Enter one or more documentation URLs (one per line):

https://wordpress.org/documentation/
https://help.zluri.com/
https://www.chargebee.com/docs/2.0/
https://support.neo.space/hc/en-us


Click Extract Modules to view the structured output.

ğŸ“¤ Output Format
[
  {
    "module": "Support & Forums",
    "Description": "Documentation related to support and forums.",
    "Submodules": {
      "Reporting security vulnerabilities": "Steps to responsibly report vulnerabilities...",
      "What do I put in the title of my post?": "Best practices for writing support requests..."
    }
  }
]

ğŸ§  Approach & Design Decisions
Crawling

Recursive crawling restricted to documentation-related URLs

Prevents homepage/UI noise and infinite crawling

Handles redirects and broken links gracefully

Content Extraction

Removes headers, footers, navigation, scripts

Supports multiple documentation layouts:

WordPress

Chargebee

Zluri

Zendesk (Neo)

Module Inference

Modules inferred using:

Page title keywords

URL path signals

Submodules inferred from:

Page-level titles (h1)

Descriptions built only from extracted content

âš ï¸ Assumptions

Documentation is publicly accessible

HTML content is available without authentication

No JavaScript rendering is required (no Selenium used)

Structure is inferred from headings and semantic content

ğŸš§ Known Limitations

Some platforms (e.g., WordPress.org) do not expose clean category pages
â†’ In such cases, content is grouped under General Documentation

JavaScript-heavy portals may limit depth of extraction

Deeply nested documentation may be partially flattened

These limitations are intentional design trade-offs to keep the solution efficient, compliant, and deterministic.

